as needed in the future. The consultant will need specialist knowledge of urban development 
management within the Asia and Pacific region. In addition, a working knowledge of disaster 
risk management and climate change adaptation will be important. The consultant will 
(i)  collaborate  with  RSDD  disaster  risk  management  and  CCA  staff  and  other 
technical  consultants  on  the  project’s  design  and  planning,  and  develop  an 
implementation and reporting schedule; 
(ii)  review past work on urban risk indicators;  
(iii)  engage, throughout the project, with development partners on the potential to 
include  urban  risk  indicators  in  other  disaster  risk  reduction  and  urban 
development monitoring initiatives; 
(iv)  assist in conducting a workshop with selected cities to review experience and 
identify requirements for indicators to measure progress on urban risk reduction 
and adaptation; 
(v)  meet  and  correspond  with  sector  development  specialists  at  ADB  and 
development  partners  to  gather  input  on  relevant  indicators  for  disaster  risk 
management and adaptation; 
(vi)  develop a draft set of indicators; 
(vii)  conduct site visits to review and test indicators; and 
(viii)  finalize a set of indicators and guidance for using the indicators.
